         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">10/6/76. ¶  ¶ As you have done with the Liliaceae, dear Mr Bentham, ¶  I will make arrangements for the despatch of the Cyperaceae (2 large cases) at an early date. ¶  ¶ I cannot see, why the Restiace...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.06.10b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 178.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS black-edged; M's brother-in-law, Eduard Wehl, died on 11 February 1876.</p>
               </note>10/6/76.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As you have done with the <name key="Liliaceae">Liliaceae</name>, dear Mr Bentham,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See G. Bentham to M, 13 April 1876 (in this edition as 76-04-13a).</p>
               </note> I will make arrangements for the despatch of the <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name> (2 large cases) at an early date.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I cannot see, why the <name key="Restiaceae">Restiaceae</name> should occupy you long, after the most careful research bestowed by me already on them. Indeed so great has been my care given to that order of plants, that I must in justice claim the quotation of the pages of the fragmenta under the respective species.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M's major treatment of the <name key="Restiaceae">Restiaceae</name> is in B73.08.01, pp. 64-<seg style="color: #000000; ">101. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, pp. 208-46 cited M's treatment. See also Lucas (2003)</seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have again demanded the Palms for you from Mr Wendland,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note> who has them since half a dozen years. I have not even yet seen a single copy of the print on them by Dr Drude and Mr Wendland,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">H. Wendland &amp; Drude (1875).</p>
               </note>
               <seg style="font-weight: bold; "> </seg>but I told Drude &amp; Grisebach,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letters not found.</p>
               </note> that though S[c]heffer<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Probably Scheffer (1873).</p>
               </note> followed similar views yet I could not see any advantages in the needless multiplication of genera, when all really good research of recent times tended to simplify them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>At last, as the proverb says, we shall not be able to see the forest for trees, standing in the way.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With best regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
